# To "brute force" the behavior of bots, you shouldn't just throw random numbers at a backtester. Instead, you need to reverse-engineer the "Noise" you found in your plots. If you can replicate the specific ways other bots are "wrong," you can build a strategy that is specifically "right."## Part 1: Brute-Forcing the Bot Behavior (Monte Carlo Setup)To decode the Brownian motion of the market, you need to simulate two components: the Global Drift (the trend) and the Micro-Inefficiency (the bot behavior).Step 1: Define the "Adversary" Bot ProfilesBased on your plots (especially 04 and 10), we can identify two main bot behaviors to brute force:The Desperate Liquidator (Bleeding Orders): These bots cross the spread regardless of price.The Mean-Reverter (The Oscillator): These bots keep the mid-price bouncing.Step 2: The Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE)Model the mid-price using a Geometric Brownian Motion (GBM) with an added "Mean Reversion" term (Ornstein-Uhlenbeck) to account for the oscillations you saw in Plot 07:$$dP_t = \theta (\mu - P_t)dt + \sigma dW_t$$$\theta$ (Speed of Reversion): Derived from the frequency of oscillations in Plot 10.$\sigma$ (Volatility): Derived from the rolling vol in Plot 11.Step 3: Brute-Force Simulation LoopGenerate a Price Path: Use the SDE above to create 1,000 "Possible Futures" for ASH and PEPPER.Inject Order Flow: For every timestamp, randomly decide if a bot "hits" your book.Buy Probability: $0.5 + (\text{Order Imbalance})$.Price Level: Use the "Two Modes" from Plot 04. 70% of trades happen at Level 1, 30% "bleed" into Level 2 or 3.The "Decode" Step: Run your current algorithm against these 1,000 paths. Identify which paths cause your PnL to drop. Those paths represent the market conditions where you are being "adversarially selected."